metadata.name: Bound #93
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten – it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself – the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold – new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we’ve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.

---

Press ‘1’-’9’ to increase resolution
Press 's' to save an image of the output at the current resolution

Created with p5.js
For third party license information, please see license.md

---

TENDER x David Brice Allen
July 2022

metadata.name: Secret Stairways #34
metadata.description:
"Secret Stairways" is a project that uses principles of Cellular Automaton to construct buildings that can remember a castle, villages...Wich I have many inspirations in architecture and buildings from the place I live (Minas Gerais).

This project use only points() and shadows(the colors) in its rendering, the algorithm randoms sorts to 5000-9000 points for each iteration. So rendering time can take a while depending of ammount of points the algo has sorted. 
Can take from 30 seconds to 1 minute to full render, after it the textures are instantly applied.

// 5 Shadow Colors
// 5 Background Colors


Works properly on Chromium based Web Browsers.






-Press "S" to save a .png file of the artwork


This is a project in p5.js



Omar Lobato,
08/03/2022.

metadata.name: Junkspace #41
metadata.description:
You never notice, it is passthrough. It is familiar but unfamiliar. It is everywhere and nowhere at the same time. It can contain anything, but it doesn't. Being here is lonely, even surrounded. It is the debris of modern architecture. It is the uncanny valley of the places. It is the Junkspace.

Junkspace is an algorithm inspired by the well-known namesake article of Rem Koolhaas (October, Vol. 100, Obsolescence. (Spring, 2002), pp. 175-190). The work is a generative approach to visualize it in the plan view. There are several paper types, partitions, floorings, and color palettes to achieve the residue of modernization.

This work exists thanks to the p5js library. To give some back to the community, you will contribute to the Processing Foundation by collecting this work.

Press "s" to save the image.

metadata.name: <iframes> #276
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Varillas #184
metadata.description:
'Varillas' is a series of 250 generative artworks. 

My goal was to generate the sensation of organized randomness.

Several followers noted the similarity of many artworks generated by this system to Mikado. In Argentina Mikado is known as 'chinese sticks'. 'Varillas' are long thin rods of wood or metal, in this case generative.

metadata.name: Kinetograms #490
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.

metadata.name: Alleles #124
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Exploration of the information provided suggests subject may exhibit frequent periods of disassociation and psychological projection, yet also has the potential to display a high degree of cognitive plasticity and persistence. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 122-130cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 66-70 years.

metadata.name: Whirled Peas #2
metadata.description:
Help us spread “Whirled Peas!”

Whirled Peas is a never-before attempted take on NFT (Non Fungible Tokens), but unlike NFTs that have come before, this will be a collective effort to raise money for vulnerable Ukrainian women, LGBTQIA+ people, and disabled refugees who are displaced and endangered by the war as part of the GISH “Change A Life: Ukraine” charity initiative to benefit Legacy of War Foundation and Random Acts.

This collaborative art piece by Misha Collins and Shawn Kemp is being unleashed into the NFT community as part of GISH (the Greatest International Scavenger Hunt), which runs from July 30 - Aug 6. Minting is open to GISH participants only via rolling whitelist spots through August 6, 2022, but after minting, anyone can purchase a Whirled Peas NFT. After the GISH Hunt ends August 6, 2022 at 10 PM PDT, all additional editions will be burned and no additional art will be generated, so there will be limited numbers of this art piece available.

GISH participants will need the support of the fxhash community who understand how generative art works and who have a few tez(ꜩ)  to donate to the cause, so if you want to help, please find a #WhirledPeas GISH player on social media, hook them up with a few tez(ꜩ) and help them learn about minting on fxhash. 

100% of the mint and 25% of each secondary sale (the maximum portion allowable on the platform) goes to our charity initiative (minus gas and platform fees). Additionally, we ask that anyone collecting this NFT through the week of August 6 do so as a part of our charity campaign and, on your honor, promise to donate 100% of your profits to this charity initiative as well by transferring it to the charity wallet (tz2SBWGZn7mf4UxoPv6tD1HM3sVvFx2EWKtA). Then, re-list it to keep it circulating to help vulnerable Ukrainians — kind of like a virtual game of hot potato, but with NFT art. After August 6, we welcome you to buy and sell it as you normally would, though we still hope you donate some or all of your profits to the cause. Of course, we can’t control what sellers down the chain choose to do, but we are grateful for your support of this charity initiative. Thank you for helping us to help Ukrainians.

Learn More - https://alleditions.art/p/whirled-peas

metadata.name: a manifested realization #63
metadata.description:
In general, this piece continues my study of procedural abstract expressionism. However, I've developed a new small bit of code I am testing here; I am trying to create a "clumping" noise function that looks natural but doesn't have the obvious "look" of Perlin noise, and is more controllable. This piece contains my first public use of this. So it is, in a way, a test. 

I was inspired by the IRL paintings of Francesco D'Adamo, specifically his "Manifesti" series, although (as is the way of things) the end result looks nothing like what I started with, and is a more general 1950s abstract expressionism look. 

This piece is a gift to the collectors of all my recent "a" mints. Thank you all!
